e the occasion of the three hundredth anniversary of Paradise Lost (1667). There is one addition of the series -- Mr. J.B. Trapp's contribution containing twenty-eight illustrations which comprise one of the largest collections of iconography of the Fall of Man. All the lectures are published in the order they were delivered; this order was not premeditated and neither was the nature of the series. The lecturers were simply invited to speak on Paradise Lost: the particular approach was subject only to their interests. The variety is wide, ranging from literary and doctrinal aspects of the work to its musical and iconographic extensions. The initial aim has been achieved. As the editor states, "This tribute to Milton is a joint Anglo-American enterprise, in keeping with our ever-increasing awareness that our study of Paradise Lost (as all of great literature) is advanced most when we expose ourselves to one and another’s' insights."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFall of man in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aArthos, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroadbent, J. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockbank, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Merritt Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuntley, Frank L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatrides, C.A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrince, F.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadzin